A: You are writing to the PrintWriter without a newline character. The BufferedReader reads until it finds a newline character, so it's reading all the data you've written to the PrintWriter without waiting for a newline.
You should write a newline character after each write:
printWriter.write("1\n");
printWriter.write("2\n");
printWriter.write("3\n");

This tells the BufferedReader to stop reading when it sees a newline character.

A: You can use PrintWriter's println method to write a line terminator.
printWriter.println("1");
printWriter.println("2");
printWriter.println("3");

This will automatically add a newline character at the end of each string, which should make the BufferedReader's readLine method return each line separately.

